Exploratory Data Analysis of Twitter Archive: WeRateDogs¶

After completing the data wrangling of the Twitter Archive, a process that required gathering, assessing and cleaning the data, the cleaned dataset was then explored to draw insight.

A describe function on the new dataset gave the result below:

pd.describe() showing summary statistics of the wrangled dataset

Insights¶

The summary statistics shows mean dog ratings of 12 and a maximum of 2195. The maximum number is too far from the mean dog ratings and could be an outlier when plotted. When queried however, the row returned an empty dataframe.

The first prediction confidence from the summary statistics shows a 1.0 max probablity which means the model was 100% sure in its prediction. The location showed the first and third predictions as a "jigsaw puzzle" and a "doormat". Further analysis using the image_url to the WeRatesDog twitter page showed that the prediction wasn't 100% accurate as there was a dog named Shaggy in the image but the jigsaw puzzle took up most of the image and likely led to the first prediction.

Further insights with Visual Analysis¶

From the dataset, visualisations were created and to answer questions asked.

1. Which dog type is most popular?¶

The bar chart above shows that "pupper" is the most popular dog type among the dogs rated by WeRateDogs.

2. How did favorite and retweet count improve over time?¶

Observing the trend above, it can be noticed that retweet and favourite count remain relatively the same in the beginning with a few outliers in favourite count. At about September 2016 into 2017, the favourite count increases significantly up to 30000 in number with little change in retweet count.

Conclusion:¶

  1. Pupper was the most frequent dog stage posted in the WeRateDogs twitter page
  2. Retweet and follower counts increased over time with favourite count having more significant increase around the end of 2016
  3. Some of the predictions were not as accurate
